# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1934-detroit-tigers-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1894-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1894 throughout the world.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] The **1900 Detroit Tigers season** was the Tigers' first in the American League, which received recognition as a major league one year later in 1901.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in fourth place out of eight teams with a record of 71–67, 12+1⁄2 games behind Charles Comiskey's Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit's home games were played at Bennett Park.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Outfielder Dick Harley led the team with a .325 batting average, 77 runs scored, and 47 stolen bases.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Sport McAllister led in slugging percentage (.383), and Frank Dillon led in extra-base hits (30).
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Roscoe Miller led the team with a 19–9 win-loss record for a .679 win percentage.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Jack Cronin led in innings pitched (372) and strikeouts (121).
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Burns and George Stallings had spent large sums of money for "releases of star players" and had paid "major league salaries" to the majority of the players.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1901 Chicago White Stockings season** was their first season as a major league team, and their second season in Chicago.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] It was also the inaugural season of American League as a major league.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings had a very balanced lineup, which was led by outfielders Dummy Hoy and Fielder Jones, and scored the most runs in the AL.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] They relied primarily on speed, as Frank Isbell, Sam Mertes, and Jones finished 1–2–3 in stolen bases.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The pitching staff was anchored by Clark Griffith, who went 24–7 with a 2.67 ERA.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The **1901 Detroit Tigers season** was the Tigers' 2nd season in Major League Baseball.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The team was a charter member of the American League, which was originally formed as the minor-league Western League, of which it had also been a charter member.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in third place with a record or 74–61, 8+1⁄2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Most of Detroit's home games were played at Bennett Park, with Sunday games played at Burns Park due to Detroit's blue laws.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Roscoe Miller (23–13) led the team in wins and was the Tigers' first 20-game winner.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] His performance headlined a strong pitching staff that had the third lowest ERA (3.30) in the American League.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Joe Yeager had an ERA of 2.61, for the second best Adjusted ERA+ in the AL, behind Cy Young.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The offense was not as strong however, scoring 741 runs – fifth among the eight teams in the league.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The team's best hitters were shortstop Kid Elberfeld (.308 average) and center fielder Jimmy Barrett (.293 average; 110 runs).
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers had played their games at Bennett Park since 1896, but the graduation to a major league meant that there would now be games scheduled on Sundays, which was forbidden by Detroit's blue laws.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] In order to avoid running afoul of this stricture, owner James D.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Burns built a ballpark on his own property in Springwells Township, Michigan just outside the Detroit city limits.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Named Burns Park, the Tigers would play their Sunday home games there for the 1901 and 1902 seasons.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] During the 1901 season, Detroit attracted 259,430 fans at home and 238,100 on the road, for a total of 447,428.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit ranked third behind Chicago and Boston in overall attendance.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] 1902 was the second year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the newly formed American League.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in seventh place with a record of 58–77 (.385), 30½ games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The 1902 Tigers were outscored by their opponents 657 runs to 566.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 189,469, sixth out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit's blue laws prevented the Tigers from playing baseball at Bennett Park on Sundays.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] As a result, the Tigers played their Sunday home games for the season at Burns Park; a stadium constructed by owner James D.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1902 Philadelphia Athletics season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team finished first in the American League with a record of 83 wins and 53 losses.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] In 1902, the Philadelphia Phillies obtained an injunction, effective only in Pennsylvania, barring Athletics' second baseman Nap Lajoie from playing baseball for any team other than the Phillies.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] Lajoie had played for the Athletics in 1901, and appeared in just one game in 1902 before the injunction went into effect.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The American League responded by transferring Lajoie's contract to the Cleveland Bronchos, who were subsequently known as the "Naps" in Lajoie's honor for several seasons.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] Following the A's pennant winning season, the *Philadelphia Inquirer* organized a championship parade for the team through the city on Monday night, September 30, 1902.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team proceeded in open carriages and were reviewed by Philadelphia Mayor Ashbridge in front of the *Inquirer'*s building on Market Street.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] "There were more than 25,000 base ball enthusiasts from Philadelphia and nearly every town within a radius of twenty miles of the city in the parade.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] A thousand effigies of the "white elephant" were carried by the paraders.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] There were fifteen bands and twenty fife and drum corps in line to furnish music for the marchers." It was estimated that more than 200,000 turned out for the parade.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The **1903 Boston Americans season** was the third season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans finished first in the American League (AL) with a record of 91 wins and 47 losses, 14+1⁄2 games ahead of the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston went on to participate in the first World Series held between the AL and National League (NL) champions.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans won the 1903 World Series in eight games over the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team was managed by Jimmy Collins and played its home games at Huntington Avenue Grounds.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Prior to the regular season, the team held spring training in Macon, Georgia.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Cy Young was a coach for the Mercer University baseball team, also based in Macon.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Boston Americans played an exhibition game against Mercer University (with Cy Young pitching for Mercer) on March 23; the outcome being a 13─2 victory for Boston.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest losing streak was three games, which occurred twice; April 20–23 and September 22–23.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest game was 12 innings, which occurred three times.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 13 home runs and had 104 RBIs, and Patsy Dougherty with a .331 batting average.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] It was Freeman's third consecutive season with at least 100 RBIs.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 40 appearances (35 starts) and pitched 34 complete games with a 28–9 record and 2.08 ERA, while striking out 176 in 341+2⁄3 innings.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had two other 20-game winners; Bill Dinneen (21–13) and Tom Hughes (20–7).
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had three games end in a tie; July 31 at Washington, August 29 at Washington, and September 25 vs.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Tie games are not counted in league standings, but player statistics during tie games are counted.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston had an 11-game winning streak from May 28 through June 8, to put themselves in the AL lead.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] While they briefly fell into second place in mid-June, behind Philadelphia, Boston then won 9-of-10 to recapture the lead, which they held through the end of the season.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans met the Pittsburgh Pirates in the first modern World Series, an agreement between the AL and the NL as a post-season tournament.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The "Amerks" won the best-of-nine series in eight games; after falling behind, 3–1, they won four games in a row, clinching the championship at their home field, the Huntington Avenue Grounds, in Boston.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] The **1934 Detroit Tigers season** was the 34th season for the Detroit Tigers since entering the American League in 1901.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers won the American League pennant with a record of 101–53, the best winning percentage in team history.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] The team made its fourth World Series appearance, but lost the 1934 World Series to the St.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] The 1933 Detroit Tigers finished fifth in the American League with a record of 75–79, 25 games behind the Washington Senators.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] In mid-December 1933, team owner Frank Navin took two key steps to strengthen his team for the 1934 season.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] On December 12, 1933, the Tigers announced that they had purchased Mickey Cochrane from Connie Mack and the Philadelphia Athletics in exchange for Johnny Pasek and cash.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers announced that they intended to use Cochrane as both a player and the team's manager.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] One day later, on December 13, 1933, the Tigers' new manager Cochrane negotiated a trade that brought outfielder Goose Goslin to the Tigers in exchange for Johnny Stone.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers won the American League pennant with a record of 101–53, finishing seven games ahead of the New York Yankees, and compiling the best winning percentage in Detroit Tigers history (either before or after).
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] They outscored their opponents 958 to 708 and also finished 1st in attendance with 919,161.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] Hall of Famer Mickey Cochrane was hired as the team's manager and catcher in the off-season before the 1934 season started.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] Cochrane was acquired by the Tigers on December 12, 1933, from the Philadelphia Athletics for Johnny Pasek and $100,000.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] Known as "Black Mike", Cochrane is considered one of the greatest catchers of all time.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] In 1934, he won the American League's Most Valuable Player award, batting .320 with a .428 on-base percentage, 76 RBIs, and 32 doubles.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] He was the first catcher to win the American League MVP award Aside from his contributions as a player, Cochrane was invaluable as a manager and leader.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] Second baseman Charlie Gehringer later said: "When Mickey was managing the Tigers from behind the plate I can't remember him ever fouling up anything.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] The Detroit infield in the mid-1930s was one of the best-hitting combinations in major league history.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] Three members of the 1934 Tigers infield (Gehringer, Owen and Rogell) played in all 154 games, and the fourth (Greenberg) played in 153.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] Shortstop **Billy Rogell** had the best offensive season of his career in 1934, hitting .296, driving in 100 runs and scoring 114.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] He spent much of the season batting fifth, frequently hitting after Cochrane, Gehringer, and Goslin and ahead of Greenberg, all four of whom were future Hall of Famers.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] Rogell, unbeknownst to the Cardinals or the media, played the 1934 World Series on a broken ankle.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] Despite the injury he was able to collect eight hits and drive in four runs over the seven-game series.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] He also found his way into one of the most popular plays in World Series history.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] After driving in a run with a single to right in the fourth inning of Game 4, Spud Davis was replaced by Hall of Famer Dizzy Dean as a pinch runner at first base.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] Pepper Martin then stepped in and hit a ground ball to Gehringer at second.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] Gehringer turned and threw to Rogell who forced out Dean at second, and then fired the ball squarely into Dean's forehead on the relay throw to first.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] The ball ricocheted off Dean's head and landed over a hundred feet away in the outfield.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] In the outfield, Hall of Famer Goose Goslin played in left field, Pete Fox was the primary right fielder, and the speedy Jo-Jo White and Gee Walker shared most of the responsibility for center field, with White playing in 92 games there (and 100 total games in the outfield).
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] Center fielder **Jo-Jo White** hit .313, scored 97 runs, had a .419 on-base percentage, and led the team with 28 stolen bases.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] White's real first name was Joyner, but he was called "Jo-Jo" because of the way he pronounced his native state of Georgia.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] The pitching staff was led by starters Tommy Bridges, Schoolboy Rowe, Elden Auker, and Alvin Crowder, who joined the team in August.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers' #4 starter was **Vic Sorrell**.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers did not employ a closer in the modern sense, as their 14 team saves were recorded by 9 different pitchers.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] **Firpo Marberry** and **Elon Hogsett** led the way with three saves each.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] Marberry was one of the first relief specialists in the major leagues, though he also started many games.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] In 1934, Marberry appeared in 38 games, starting 19 and finishing 14, and had a record of 15–5.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] Elon "Chief" Hogsett became a fan favorite as well, having a 3–2 record in 26 games.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] The 1934 World Series was a match-up between the St.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] Louis Cardinals' "Gashouse Gang" and Detroit's "G-Men" (so named because of stars Gehringer, Greenberg, and Goslin).
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] Even nearly 50 years later, Charlie Gehringer (interviewed in 1982) felt the Tigers were robbed of the 1934 championship by umpire Brick Owens.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers wound up losing Game 6 by one run.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] They then lost Game 7 in an 11–0 shutout thrown by Dizzy Dean, despite a 2-for-4 game from Gehringer.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] In the sixth inning of Game 7, Joe Medwick slid hard into Marv Owen, the Tigers' third baseman, after hitting a triple.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] They tangled briefly, and when Medwick went to his position in left field, the Detroit fans, knowing the game was lost (the score was 9–0 by then), vented their frustrations on Medwick, throwing fruit, vegetables, bottles, cushions, etc., at him.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] Commissioner Landis ordered Medwick benched to end the ruckus.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] Newsreel footage shows Medwick slamming his glove onto the dugout bench in disgust.
[src:1934-detroit-tigers-season/1934-detroit-tigers-season] Pete Fox played for the Tigers and became the only World Series player to hit six (6) doubles in any Series of any length.
